# Next.js App Router Organization

## Core Principle

**Group routes by layout/purpose, not by authentication level.** Handle authentication at the page level, not through folder structure.

## Route Grouping Strategy

### ✅ Good: Group by Layout/Purpose

```sh
app/
├─ (marketing)/              # Marketing layout (different header/footer)
│  ├─ layout.tsx             # Marketing-specific layout
│  ├─ page.tsx               # Homepage
│  ├─ about/
│  │  └─ page.tsx
│  └─ pricing/
│     └─ page.tsx
├─ (app)/                    # Main app layout (navigation, user menu)
│  ├─ layout.tsx             # App-specific layout
│  ├─ dashboard/
│  │  └─ page.tsx            # Protected via page-level check
│  ├─ items/
│  │  ├─ page.tsx            # List page
│  │  ├─ [id]/
│  │  │  └─ page.tsx         # Detail page
│  │  └─ new/
│  │     └─ page.tsx         # Create page (protected)
│  └─ account/
│     └─ page.tsx            # Protected via page-level check
└─ auth/                     # Auth layout (centered, minimal)
   ├─ layout.tsx             # Auth-specific layout
   ├─ login/
   │  └─ page.tsx
   └─ signup/
      └─ page.tsx
```

**Why this works:**
- Clear visual/UX separation (marketing vs app vs auth)
- Easy to find routes by feature
- Layouts match user experience
- Auth requirements can change without moving files

### ❌ Bad: Group by Auth Level

```sh
app/
├─ (public)/       # ❌ Breaks down quickly
│  ├─ page.tsx
│  ├─ about/
│  └─ items/       # What if this needs auth later?
├─ (protected)/    # ❌ Routes move frequently
│  ├─ account/
│  └─ dashboard/   # Auth requirements change
└─ (auth)/
   ├─ login/
   └─ signup/
```

**Why this fails:**
- Auth requirements change frequently
- Moving files is tedious and error-prone
- Mixed concerns (layout + protection)
- Harder to reason about

## Route Groups Explained

Route groups use `(folder)` syntax and **don't affect URL structure**:

```sh
app/
├─ (marketing)/
│  └─ about/
│     └─ page.tsx   # URL: /about (not /marketing/about)
└─ (app)/
   └─ dashboard/
      └─ page.tsx   # URL: /dashboard (not /app/dashboard)
```

**Use route groups when:**
- Different sections need different layouts
- You want to organize files without affecting URLs
- You have distinct visual/UX sections (marketing, app, admin)

**Don't use route groups when:**
- You only want to group by auth (use page-level checks instead)
- You want the folder name in the URL (just use regular folders)

## Page-Level Protection

Handle authentication at the page level:

### Server Component (Redirect Pattern)

```tsx
// app/(app)/dashboard/page.tsx
import { getServerSession } from '@/lib/services/auth/server';
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation';

export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const session = await getServerSession();
  
  if (!session) {
    redirect('/auth/login');
  }

  return <div>Protected content</div>;
}
```

### Client Component (Conditional Render Pattern)

```tsx
// app/(app)/account/page.tsx
'use client';
import { Authenticated, Unauthenticated } from 'convex/react';

export default function AccountPage() {
  return (
    <>
      <Authenticated>
        <AccountContent />
      </Authenticated>
      <Unauthenticated>
        <LoginPrompt />
      </Unauthenticated>
    </>
  );
}
```

## File Conventions

### Page Files

```sh
error.tsx       # Error UI (Error boundary)
layout.tsx      # Shared layout (wraps all child routes)
loading.tsx     # Loading UI (Suspense boundary)
not-found.tsx   # 404 UI
page.tsx        # Required for route to be accessible
```

### Dynamic Routes

```sh
app/
├─ items/
│  ├─ page.tsx         # /items
│  ├─ [slug]/
│  │  └─ page.tsx      # /items/some-item-slug
│  └─ [id]/
│     └─ edit/
│        └─ page.tsx   # /items/123/edit
```

### API Routes

```sh
app/
└─ api/
   ├─ auth/
   │  └─ [...all]/
   │     └─ route.ts   # Catch-all: /api/auth/*
   └─ webhooks/
      └─ stripe/
         └─ route.ts   # /api/webhooks/stripe
```

## Layout Hierarchy

Layouts nest from root to leaf:

```tsx
// app/layout.tsx (Root Layout - Required)
export default function RootLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <html>
      <body>
        <Providers>
          {children}
        </Providers>
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}

// app/(app)/layout.tsx (App Layout)
export default function AppLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <>
      <AppHeader />
      <Sidebar />
      <main>{children}</main>
    </>
  );
}

// app/(marketing)/layout.tsx (Marketing Layout)
export default function MarketingLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <>
      <MarketingHeader />
      <main>{children}</main>
      <Footer />
    </>
  );
}
```

**Rendering hierarchy:**

```sh
Root Layout
  ├─ App Layout
  │  └─ Dashboard Page
  └─ Marketing Layout
     └─ About Page
```

## Best Practices

### 1. Keep Pages Simple

```tsx
// ✅ Page delegates to components
export default function ItemsPage() {
  return <ItemList />;
}

// ❌ Page has too much logic
export default function ItemsPage() {
  const [filter, setFilter] = useState('all');
  const items = useItems();
  const filtered = items?.filter(...);
  // 50 more lines...
}
```

### 2. Co-locate Route-Specific Code

Use `_` prefix for private directories — Next.js ignores folders starting with `_`.

```sh
app/
└─ items/
   ├─ page.tsx              # Main page
   ├─ _components/          # Page-specific components
   │  ├─ item-filters.tsx
   │  └─ item-stats.tsx
   └─ [id]/
      └─ page.tsx
```

For route groups with shared concerns across multiple pages, use `_hooks/` and `_queries/` at the group level:

```sh
app/
└─ @panel/
   ├─ _components/          # Shared components for this route group
   ├─ _hooks/               # Client hooks scoped to this group
   ├─ _queries/             # Server queries scoped to this group
   └─ (.)items/edit/[id]/
      ├─ page.tsx
      └─ _components/       # Page-specific components
```

Feature-specific code belongs in `src/features/{domain}/`. Route-level directories are for cross-feature concerns scoped to a route group (e.g., aggregating multiple entities for dropdowns, navigation hooks specific to a UI pattern).

### 3. Use Metadata API

```tsx
// app/(marketing)/about/page.tsx
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'About Us',
  description: 'Learn more about our mission',
};

export default function AboutPage() {
  return <div>About content</div>;
}
```

### 4. Group Related Routes

```sh
# ✅ Good: Related features together
app/(app)/
└─ items/
   ├─ page.tsx         # List
   ├─ [id]/
   │  ├─ page.tsx      # View
   │  └─ edit/
   │     └─ page.tsx   # Edit
   └─ new/
      └─ page.tsx      # Create

# ❌ Bad: Scattered
app/(app)/
├─ items-list/
├─ items-detail/
├─ edit-item/
└─ new-item/
```

## Common Patterns

### Loading States

```tsx
// app/(app)/items/loading.tsx
export default function Loading() {
  return <ItemsListSkeleton />;
}

// Automatically wraps page.tsx in Suspense
```

### Error Boundaries

```tsx
// app/(app)/items/error.tsx
'use client';
export default function Error({ error, reset }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Something went wrong!</h2>
      <button onClick={reset}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Parallel Routes (Advanced)

```sh
app/
└─ dashboard/
   ├─ page.tsx
   ├─ @analytics/
   │  └─ page.tsx          # Renders in parallel
   └─ layout.tsx           # Receives analytics as prop
```

## Decision Tree

**Should I use a route group?**
- ✅ Different layouts needed? → Use `(group)`
- ✅ Organize without URL impact? → Use `(group)`
- ❌ Only for auth? → No, use page-level checks
- ❌ Want folder in URL? → No, use regular folder

**Where should protection happen?**
- ✅ Individual page needs auth? → Page-level check
- ✅ Whole section needs auth? → Layout-level check
- ❌ Folder-based protection? → No, use page/layout checks

**Should this be a page or component?**
- ✅ Needs a URL? → `page.tsx`
- ✅ Reusable across pages? → `components/` (shared)
- ✅ Used only on this page? → `app/page-name/_components/` (page-specific)
